# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1810-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The **11th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1809, to March 4, 1811, during the first two years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1814; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1810; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1812.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their districts.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] There were 8 resignations, 2 deaths, 1 interim appointment, and 1 vacancy from before this Congress.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 12 resignations, 1 death, and 1 change due to a contested election.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1776-in-the-united-states] 1776 is celebrated in the United States as the official beginning of the nation, with the Declaration of Independence of the Thirteen Colonies from the British Empire issued on July 4.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1777-in-the-united-states] Events from the year **1777 in the United States**.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1778-in-the-united-states] Events from the year **1778 in the United States**.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1779-in-the-united-states] Events from the year **1779 in the United States**.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1780-in-the-united-states] Events from the year **1780 in the United States**.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1781-in-the-united-states] Events from the year **1781 in the United States**.
[src:1810-in-the-united-states/1781-in-the-united-states] This year marked the beginning of government under the Articles of Confederation as well as the surrender of British armed forces in the American Revolution.
